[3
Date: Fri, 05 Nov 1999 17:43:58 -0200
From: Celso Ferreira Ramos Filho <celso@cives.ufrj.br>
Centro de Informacao em Saude para Viajantes - Cives

The text on Aircraft Disinsection Requirements (West Nile-like virus,
aircraft spraying (03) 991025230628) lists South Africa as mandating cabin
spraying for planes coming from areas infected with malaria or yellow fever.
That is probably why, last August [1999, the SAA [South African Airways
plane I was in, arriving from Sao Paulo city (actually, nearby Guarulhos)
was duly sprayed. This is perhaps funny, since Sao Paulo city is not -- and
has never been -- an area of occurrence of either disease.
Bureaucratic execution of technical directives can indeed be funny:
during my stay in Africa, I had occasion to arrive at the same South
African airport (Johannesburg) thrice: arriving from Kenya, from
Namibia, and from Zimbabwe. In none of these instances was the plane
sprayed.
--
Celso Ferreira Ramos-Filho, MD
Associate Professor, Department of Preventive Medicine
Federal University of Rio de Janeiro
Brazil
<celso@cives.ufrj.br>
